<item>
  <title>Defining the \(L^2\) Space of \(k\)-Forms on Riemannian Manifolds</title>
  <dc:creator>Ian McPherson</dc:creator>
  <link>https://mcphersonianoliver.github.io/blog-posts/fundamentals/2026-1-21-L2-on-k-forms.html</link>
  <description><![CDATA[ 




<div class="abstract-container">
<p><span class="abstract-header">ABSTRACT</span> In order to define the Laplacian on Riemannian manifold <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(M,g)">, one needs to define the space it acts on (or at least a dense subset). This post defines the Riemannian volume form, and the <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?L%5E2"> space of functions (and more general <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-forms) on Riemannian manifolds. This will allow for the development of the Laplacian operator in this more general setting in later posts.</p>
</div>
<p><strong>Setting.</strong> Let <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(M,%20g)"> be a Riemannian manifold of dimension <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n"> with metric tensor <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g">. The metric induces an inner product on the tangent space <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?T_%7Bx%7DM"> at each point <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?x%20%5Cin%20M">, denoted by <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g(v,w)"> for vectors <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?v,w%20%5Cin%20T_%7Bx%7DM">.</p>
<p>In the Euclidean case, the Laplacian operator <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5CDelta"> is defined on function <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?f%20%5Cin%20L%5E%7B2%7D(%5Cmathbb%7BR%7D%5E%7Bn%7D)"> by the operation</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5CDelta%20f%20%20=%20-%20%5Csum_%7Bi=1%7D%5E%7Bn%7D%20%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial%5E%7B2%7D%20f%7D%7B%5Cpartial%20x_%7Bi%7D%5E%7B2%7D%7D%20."></p>
<p>To generalize this to Riemannian manifolds, we first need to define the corresponding <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?L%5E%7B2%7D"> space for functions and more generally for <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-forms.</p>
<div class="definition-box">
<p><strong>Definition 1.</strong> Let <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(M,%20g)"> be a Riemannian manifold of dimension <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n">. The <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?L%5E%7B2%7D"> space of functions on <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?M"> is defined as the completion of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?C_%7Bc%7D%5E%7B%5Cinfty%7D(M)"> (the space of smooth functions with compact support) with respect to the inner product</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Clangle%20f_%7B1%7D,%20f_%7B2%7D%20%5Crangle%20=%20%5Cint_%7BM%7D%20f_%7B1%7D(x)%20f_%7B2%7D(x)%20%5C,%20dV_%7Bg%7D(x),"></p>
<p>where <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?dV_%7Bg%7D"> is the Riemannian volume form induced by the metric <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g">.</p>
</div>
<p>Functions are <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?0">-forms. We can more generally consider <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-forms on <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathcal%7BM%7D">. By the use of the musical isomorphism, we can recover an <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?L%5E%7B2%7D"> structure on this space induced by the metric tensor <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g">.</p>
<div class="definition-box">
<p><strong>Definition 2.</strong> Let <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(M,%20g)"> be a Riemannian manifold of dimension <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n">. The <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?L%5E%7B2%7D"> space of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-forms on <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?M"> is defined as the completion of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?C_%7Bc%7D%5E%7B%5Cinfty%7D(M,%20%5CLambda%5E%7Bk%7DT%5E%7B*%7DM)"> (the space of smooth <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-forms with compact support) with respect to the inner product</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Clangle%20%5Comega,%20%5Ceta%20%5Crangle%20=%20%5Cint_%7BM%7D%20g(%5Comega(x),%20%5Ceta(x))%20%5C,%20dV_%7Bg%7D(x),"></p>
<p>where <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g(%5Comega,%20%5Ceta)"> is the inner product on the space of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-forms (with abuse of notation) induced by the metric <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g">.</p>
</div>
<div class="intuition-box">
<p><strong><em>Intuition.</em></strong> The inner product on <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?0">-forms globalize the pointwise overlap (their product) of functions by integrating against the Riemannian volume form. This aggregates the pointwise overlap over the entire manifold. This is the same idea as the <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?L%5E%7B2%7D"> space of functions on Euclidean space where implicitly we use the standard Euclidean volume form.</p>
<p>More generally, for <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-forms, the pointwise inner product <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g(%5Comega,%20%5Ceta)"> measures how much the two <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-forms overlap at each point, and integrating this against the Riemannian volume form aggregates this overlap over the entire manifold. The generalizes the same underlying idea: the angle between globally defined objects (functions or <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-forms) is measured by aggregating their pointwise overlap across the manifold.</p>
</div>
<p>The discussion that follows draws heavily from <span class="citation" data-cites="rosenberg1997 tu2011">(Rosenberg 1997; Tu 2011)</span>.</p>
<section id="volume-forms" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="volume-forms">Volume Forms</h2>
<p>The Riemannian volume measure is defined by the following.</p>
<div class="definition-box">
<p><strong>Definition 3.</strong> Let <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(M,%20g)"> be a Riemannian manifold of dimension <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n">. The Riemannian volume form <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?dV_%7Bg%7D"> is defined as</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?dV_%7Bg%7D%20=%20%5Csqrt%7B%7C%20%5Cdet(g)%20%7C%7D%20%5C,%20dx%5E%7B1%7D%20%5Cwedge%20dx%5E%7B2%7D%20%5Cwedge%20%5Ccdots%20%5Cwedge%20dx%5E%7Bn%7D,"></p>
<p>where <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g"> is the matrix where <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g_%7Bij%7D"> are the components of the metric tensor in local coordinates <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(%5Cpartial_%7Bx%5E%7B1%7D%7D,%20%5Cpartial_%7Bx%5E%7B2%7D%7D,%20%5Cldots,%20%5Cpartial_%7Bx%5E%7Bn%7D%7D)"> where positively oriented basis of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?T_%7Bx%7DM">.</p>
<p>Under this formula, the volume of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(M,g)"> is given by</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Coperatorname%7BVol%7D(M)%20=%20%5Cint_%7BM%7D%20dV_%7Bg%7D(x)."></p>
</div>
<section id="heuristic-derivation" class="level3">
<h3 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="heuristic-derivation">(Heuristic) Derivation</h3>
<p>To see where this formula comes from, we consider recovering the volume of a set <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?U%20%5Csubset%20M"> by summing up volumes of infinitessimal boxes within the tangent spaces <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?T_%7Bx%7DM"> for <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?x%20%5Cin%20U">. This recovers the familiar idea for the Euclidean setting, where the volume of a set <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?U%20%5Csubset%20%5Cmathbb%7BR%7D%5E%7Bn%7D"> is given by summing up volumes of infinitessimal boxes aligned with the standard basis vectors.</p>
<p>We have the following picture in mind:</p>
<div class="quarto-figure quarto-figure-center">
<figure class="figure">
<p><img src="https://mcphersonianoliver.github.io/files/images/riem-volume-form.webp" class="img-fluid figure-img"></p>
<figcaption>Volume Form from Infinitessimal Boxes Illustration</figcaption>
</figure>
</div>
<p>More concretely, consider a positively oriented coordinate neighborhood <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?U%20%5Csubset%20M"> around <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?x"> with coordinates <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(x%5E%7B1%7D,%20x%5E%7B2%7D,%20%5Cldots,%20x%5E%7Bn%7D)">. Then pick a large number of points <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5C%7Bp_%7Bj%7D%5C%7D_%7Bj=1%7D%5E%7BN%7D"> in <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?U">. For each point <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?p_%7Bj%7D">, define the infinitessimal box <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?B_%7Bj%7D%20%5Csubset%20T_%7Bp_%7Bj%7D%7DM"> with sides <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(%5CDelta%20x%5E%7B1%7D)%5Cpartial_%7Bx%5E%7B1%7D%7D,%20(%5CDelta%20x%5E%7B2%7D)%20%5Cpartial_%7Bx%5E%7B2%7D%7D,%20%5Cldots,%20(%5CDelta%20x%5E%7Bn%7D)%20%5Cpartial_%7Bx%5E%7Bn%7D%7D"> where <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5CDelta%20x%5E%7Bi%7D"> are small increments on the <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?i">-th local coordinate direction <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cpartial_%7Bx%5E%7Bi%7D%7D%20=%20%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial%7D%7B%5Cpartial%20x%5E%7Bi%7D%7D">. For each tangent space <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?T_%7Bp_%7Bj%7D%7DM">, let <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?v_1,%20v_2,%20%5Cldots,%20v_n"> be the positively oriented orthonormal basis. Then, under Einstein summation notation, we can write</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cpartial_%7Bx%5E%7Bi%7D%7D%20=%20%5Calpha_%7Bi%7D%5E%7Bk%7D%20v_%7Bk%7D,"></p>
<p>for some matrix <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Calpha%5E%7Bk%7D_%7Bi%7D">. Note that by convention, this means <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Calpha_%7Bi%7D%5E%7Bk%7D%20v_%7Bk%7D%20%5Cequiv%20%5Csum_%7Bk=1%7D%5E%7Bn%7D%20%5Calpha_%7Bi%7D%5E%7Bk%7D%20v_%7Bk%7D">.</p>
<p>We expect the volume to be</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbegin%7Baligned%7D%0A%5Coperatorname%7BVol%7D(U)%20&amp;%20=%20%5Clim_%7B%5CDelta%20x%5E%7Bi%7D%20%5Cto%200%7D%20%5Clim_%7BN%20%5Cto%20%5Cinfty%7D%20%5Csum_%7Bj=1%7D%5E%7BN%7D%20%5Coperatorname%7BVol%7D(B_%7Bj%7D)%20%5C%5C%0A&amp;%20=%20%5Clim_%7B%5CDelta%20x%5E%7Bi%7D%20%5Cto%200%7D%20%5Clim_%7BN%20%5Cto%20%5Cinfty%7D%20%5Csum_%7Bj=1%7D%5E%7BN%7D%20%5Ctext%7BVolume%20of%20Parallelepiped%20with%20$i$th%20Side%20%7D%20(%5CDelta%20%7Bx%5E%7Bi%7D%7D)%20%5Csum_%7Bk=1%7D%5E%7Bn%7D%20%5Calpha_%7Bi%7D%5E%7Bk%7Dv_%7Bk%7D%5C%5C%0A&amp;%20=%20%5Clim_%7B%5CDelta%20x%5E%7Bi%7D%20%5Cto%200%7D%20%5Clim_%7BN%20%5Cto%20%5Cinfty%7D%20%5Csum_%7Bj=1%7D%5E%7BN%7D%20%5Cleft(%20%5Cprod_%7Bi=1%7D%5E%7Bn%7D%20%5CDelta%20x%5E%7Bi%7D%20%5Cright)%20%5Cleft%7C%20%5Cdet(%5Calpha_%7Bi%7D%5E%7Bk%7D)%20%5Cright%7C%20%5C%5C%0A&amp;%20=%20%5Cint_%7BU%7D%20%5Cleft%7C%20%5Cdet(%5Calpha_%7Bi%7D%5E%7Bk%7D)%20%5Cright%7C%20dx%5E%7B1%7D%20%5Cwedge%20dx%5E%7B2%7D%20%5Cwedge%20%5Ccdots%20%5Cwedge%20dx%5E%7Bn%7D%0A%5Cend%7Baligned%7D"></p>
<p>where <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cdet(%5Calpha)"> is the absolute value of the determinant of the matrix with entries <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Calpha_%7Bi%7D%5E%7Bk%7D">. Note that in the second line we do not use the summation convention for <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?i">.</p>
<p>By definition of the metric tensor <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g">, we have that</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%0Ag_%7Bij%7D%20=%20g(%5Cpartial_%7Bx%5E%7Bi%7D%7D,%20%5Cpartial_%7Bx%5E%7Bj%7D%7D)%20=%20g(%5Calpha_%7Bi%7D%5E%7Bk%7D%20v_%7Bk%7D,%20%5Calpha_%7Bj%7D%5E%7B%5Cell%7D%20v_%7B%5Cell%7D)%20=%20%5Calpha_%7Bi%7D%5E%7Bk%7D%20%5Calpha_%7Bj%7D%5E%7B%5Cell%7D%20g(v_%7Bk%7D,%20v_%7B%5Cell%7D)%20=%20%5Calpha_%7Bi%7D%5E%7Bk%7D%20%5Calpha_%7Bj%7D%5E%7B%5Cell%7D%20%5Cdelta_%7Bk%20%5Cell%7D%20=%20%5Calpha_%7Bi%7D%5E%7Bk%7D%20%5Calpha_%7Bj%7D%5E%7Bk%7D%20=%20(AA%5E%7BT%7D)_%7Bij%7D,%0A"></p>
<p>where <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?A%20=%20(%5Calpha_%7Bi%7D%5E%7Bj%7D)">. Thus, it follows that</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cdet(g)%20=%20%5Cdet(AA%5E%7BT%7D)%20=%20%5Cdet(A)%5E%7B2%7D,"></p>
<p>and so we have that the volume form of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?U"> should be given by</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%0A%5Coperatorname%7BVol%7D(U)%20=%20%5Cint_%7BU%7D%20%5Csqrt%7B%7C%5Cdet(g)%7C%7D%20%5C,%20dx%5E%7B1%7D%20%5Cwedge%20dx%5E%7B2%7D%20%5Cwedge%20%5Ccdots%20%5Cwedge%20dx%5E%7Bn%7D.%0A"></p>
<p>This derivation is heuristic, but it provides the intuition for why the Riemannian volume form takes the form it does.</p>
<p><strong><em>Exercise.</em></strong> Verify that the volume form is a well-defined <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n">-form on <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?M">; that is, it does not depend on the choice of the positively oriented coordinate chart.</p>
</section>
</section>
<section id="l2-spaces-on-riemannian-manifolds" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="l2-spaces-on-riemannian-manifolds"><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?L%5E%7B2%7D"> Spaces on Riemannian Manifolds</h2>
<p>With the Riemannian volume form defined, we can now define the desired <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?L%5E%7B2%7D"> spaces. The first definition for functions is natural, as it generalizes the Euclidean <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?L%5E%7B2%7D"> space by replacing the standard volume form with the Riemannian volume form. The second definition for <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-forms uses the inner product on <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-forms induced by the metric tensor <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g">.</p>
<p>The rest of this section is devoted to recalling the definition of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-forms, and performing some computations to understanding the induced inner product from the metric tensor on the space of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?1">-forms and <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?2">-forms. By abuse of notation, we will denote the inner product on <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-forms induced by <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g"> also by <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g(%5Ccdot,%20%5Ccdot)">. Generally speaking, the inner product on <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-forms can be defined by extending the inner product on <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?1">-forms using the properties of the wedge product.</p>
<section id="review-of-k-forms" class="level3">
<h3 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="review-of-k-forms">Review of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-Forms</h3>
<p>Let <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?V"> be a vector space and denote <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?V%5E%7Bk%7D%20=%20V%20%5Ctimes%20%5Ccdots%20%5Ctimes%20V"> (<img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k"> times). A <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-linear function <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?f%20%5Ccolon%20V%5E%7Bk%7D%20%5Cto%20%5Cmathbb%7BR%7D"> is called alternating if for any permutation <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Csigma"> on <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5C%7B1,%202,%20%5Cldots,%20k%5C%7D">, we have that</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?f(v_%7B%5Csigma(1)%7D,%20%5Cldots,%20v_%7B%5Csigma(k)%7D)%20=%20%5Coperatorname%7Bsgn%7D(%5Csigma)%20f(v_%7B1%7D,%20%5Cldots,%20v_%7Bk%7D)."></p>
<p>Then, the following definition specializes the set of alternating <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-linear functions to when <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?V%20=%20T_%7Bp%7DM"> for some point <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?p%20%5Cin%20M">.</p>
<div class="definition-box">
<p><strong>Definition 4.</strong> Let <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?M"> be a smooth manifold and let <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?p%20%5Cin%20M">. A <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-form at <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?p"> is an alternating <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-linear function <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Comega%20%5Ccolon%20(T_%7Bp%7DM)%5E%7Bk%7D%20%5Cto%20%5Cmathbb%7BR%7D">. The set of all <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-forms at <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?p"> is denoted by <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5CLambda%5E%7Bk%7DT_%7Bp%7D%5E%7B*%7DM">.</p>
</div>
<p>There is a lot of nice properties that can be proven about <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-forms, see for instance <span class="citation" data-cites="tu2011">(Tu 2011)</span>. One important property is that if <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5C%7Be_%7B1%7D,%20e_%7B2%7D,%20%5Cldots,%20e_%7Bn%7D%5C%7D"> is a basis for an <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n">-dimensional vector space <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?V">, then the set of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-forms <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5C%7Be_%7Bi_%7B1%7D%7D%5E%7B*%7D%20%5Cwedge%20%5Ccdots%20%5Cwedge%20e_%7Bi_%7Bk%7D%7D%5E%7B*%7D%20%5Cmid%201%20%5Cleq%20i_%7B1%7D%20%3C%20i_%7B2%7D%20%3C%20%5Ccdots%20%3C%20i_%7Bk%7D%20%5Cleq%20n%5C%7D"> forms a basis for <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5CLambda%5E%7Bk%7DV%5E%7B*%7D">, where <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?e_%7Bi%7D%5E%7B*%7D"> is the dual basis element to <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?e_%7Bi%7D">. We will use this for later computations as this enables us to draw heavily from linear algebraic intuition.</p>
<p>The point of the <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-form is they allow us to integrate over <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-dimensional surfaces in <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?M"> in a <strong>coordinate-free</strong> way. We note that the Riemannian volume form defined earlier is an example of an <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n">-form on <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?M">, and the exercise earlier asked to verify that it is well-defined (i.e., coordinate-free).</p>
<p>Lastly, we mention that beyond allowing for integration over <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-dimensional surfaces, the use of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-forms is crucial in defining operators such as the exterior derivative and the Hodge star operator, which are essential in differential geometry and the study of Riemannian manifolds. We will use these operators in a later post to define the Laplacian on a Riemannian manifold in a coordinate-free way.</p>
</section>
<section id="metric-tensor-on-1-forms" class="level3">
<h3 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="metric-tensor-on-1-forms">Metric Tensor on <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?1">-Forms</h3>
<p>To warm-up to the idea of defining an inner product on <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k">-forms induced by the metric tensor <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g">, we first consider the case of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?1">-forms. Notice that <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5CLambda%5E%7B1%7DT_%7Bp%7DM%20=%20T_%7Bp%7D%5E%7B*%7DM">, the dual space of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?T_%7Bp%7DM">, and because of this association it should be clear how one would define the inner product on <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?1">-forms (hint: consider the natural isomorphism between <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?T_%7Bp%7DM"> and <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?T_%7Bp%7D%5E%7B*%7DM"> induced by <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g">).</p>
<p>Let <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Comega,%20%5Ceta%20%5Cin%20%5CLambda%5E%7B1%7DT_%7Bp%7D%5E%7B*%7DM"> be two <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?1">-forms at a point <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?p%20%5Cin%20M">. Denote the isomorphism <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Calpha%20%5Ccolon%20T_%7Bp%7DM%20%5Cto%20T_%7Bp%7D%5E%7B*%7DM"> induced by <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g"> be defined by <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Calpha_%7Bg%7D(v)%20=%20g(v,%20%5Ccdot)">. Then, we can define the inner product on <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?1">-forms by</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Clangle%20%5Comega,%20%5Ceta%20%5Crangle%20=%20g(%5Calpha%5E%7B-1%7D(%5Comega),%20%5Calpha%5E%7B-1%7D(%5Ceta))."></p>
<p>The idea behind this definition is that we can simply pull back the <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?1">-forms to vectors using the isomorphism induced by <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g">, and then use the inner product on the tangent space itself. However, we can also recover an explicit formula for this inner product in local coordinates.</p>
<p>Let <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(x%5E%7B1%7D,%20x%5E%7B2%7D,%20%5Cldots,%20x%5E%7Bn%7D)"> be local coordinates around <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?p"> and denote the corresponding basis of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?T_%7Bp%7DM"> by <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5C%7B%5Cpartial_%7Bx%5E%7B1%7D%7D,%20%5Cpartial_%7Bx%5E%7B2%7D%7D,%20%5Cldots,%20%5Cpartial_%7Bx%5E%7Bn%7D%7D%5C%7D"> and the dual basis of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?T_%7Bp%7D%5E%7B*%7DM"> by <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5C%7Bdx%5E%7B1%7D,%20dx%5E%7B2%7D,%20%5Cldots,%20dx%5E%7Bn%7D%5C%7D">. Then, we can write</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Comega%20=%20%5Comega_%7Bi%7D%20dx%5E%7Bi%7D,%20%5Cquad%20%5Ceta%20=%20%5Ceta_%7Bj%7D%20dx%5E%7Bj%7D,"></p>
<p>for some coefficients <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Comega_%7Bi%7D,%20%5Ceta_%7Bj%7D%20%5Cin%20%5Cmathbb%7BR%7D">. By definition of the isomorphism <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Calpha">, we have that</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Calpha%5E%7B-1%7D(dx%5E%7Bi%7D)%20=%20g%5E%7Bij%7D%20%5Cpartial_%7Bx%5E%7Bj%7D%7D,"></p>
<p>where <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g%5E%7Bij%7D"> are the components of the inverse matrix of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g_%7Bij%7D">. Thus, we have that</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbegin%7Baligned%7D%0A%5Clangle%20%5Comega,%20%5Ceta%20%5Crangle%20&amp;%20=%20g(%5Calpha%5E%7B-1%7D%0A(%5Comega),%20%5Calpha%5E%7B-1%7D(%5Ceta))%20%5C%5C%0A&amp;%20=%20g(%5Comega_%7Bi%7D%20%5Calpha%5E%7B-1%7D(dx%5E%7Bi%7D),%20%5Ceta%0A_%7Bj%7D%20%5Calpha%5E%7B-1%7D(dx%5E%7Bj%7D))%20%5C%5C%0A&amp;%20=%20g(%5Comega_%7Bi%7D%20g%5E%7Bik%7D%20%5Cpartial_%7Bx%5E%7Bk%7D%7D,%0A%20%20%20%20%5Ceta_%7Bj%7D%20g%5E%7Bj%20%5Cell%7D%20%5Cpartial_%7Bx%5E%7B%5Cell%7D%7D)%20%5C%5C%0A&amp;%20=%20%5Comega_%7Bi%7D%20%5Ceta_%7Bj%7D%20g%5E%7Bik%7D%20g%5E%7Bj%20%5Cell%7D%20g(%5Cpartial_%7Bx%5E%7Bk%7D%7D,%20%5Cpartial_%7Bx%5E%7B%5Cell%7D%7D)%20%5C%5C%0A&amp;%20=%20%5Comega_%7Bi%7D%20%5Ceta_%7Bj%7D%20g%5E%7Bik%7D%20g%5E%7Bj%20%5Cell%7D%20g_%7Bk%20%5Cell%7D%20%5C%5C%0A&amp;%20=%20%5Comega_%7Bi%7D%20%5Ceta_%7Bj%7D%20g%5E%7Bij%7D.%0A%5Cend%7Baligned%7D"></p>
</section>
